<div id="review_964741005" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/964741005" />
    <a title="Perry Whitford" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5485442-perry-whitford"><img alt="Perry Whitford" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1306266009p2/5485442.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/964741005?book_show_action=true">Jun 11, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Perry Whitford" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Perry Whitford" href="/user/show/5485442-perry-whitford">Perry Whitford</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="ebook " href="/book/show/13338946-the-warlord-of-mars">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer964741005" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10468047212508304583">In <i>The God&apos;s of Mars</i> it was jarring to discover that Barsoom had not one but two immense communities that nobody knew about living at the south pole. Surely there wasn&apos;t another civilization in the north pole?<br/><br/>Stone the crows, it does. The yellow men of Okar. At least the white Therns and black First Born of the south pole had an esoteric religious racket protecting them from scrutiny. The reason given for the Okars lack of transparency doesn&apos;t cut any mustard.<br/><br/>The people of Barsoom have advanced </span>
  <span id="freeText10468047212508304583" style="display:none">In <i>The God's of Mars</i> it was jarring to discover that Barsoom had not one but two immense communities that nobody knew about living at the south pole. Surely there wasn't another civilization in the north pole?<br /><br />Stone the crows, it does. The yellow men of Okar. At least the white Therns and black First Born of the south pole had an esoteric religious racket protecting them from scrutiny. The reason given for the Okars lack of transparency doesn't cut any mustard.<br /><br />The people of Barsoom have advanced airship and can travel pole to pole in hours, yet they knew nothing of their own planet before John Carter arrived. <br /><br />I only decided to read this book because I knew it was the last in the (initial) trilogy. I quickly regretted my completist's tendancies. The previous episode ended in a cliff-hanger. Burroughs swiftly botched that through his customary narrative ineptitude. What followed was merely a tired retread.<br /><br />Ok, it's a children's adventure story; that's no excuse to plot like one. The author's attempts ot creating tension only succeed in making his hero look like an idiot. Time and again John Carter failed to grasp the bleeding obvious, making one boneheaded decision after another.<br /><br />The story is packed full of sword fights, yet Burroughs knew nothing about swordplay, all he can do is keep assuring you that it's a great fight without describing it. <br /><br />Kids are better off reading comics.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10468047212508304583" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


