<div id="review_2598871720" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2598871720" />
    <a title="David B" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/24673004-david-b"><img alt="David B" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2598871720?book_show_action=true">Mar 01, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="David B" class="user" itemprop="url" name="David B" href="/user/show/24673004-david-b">David B</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2598871720" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2306483614444198526">John Carter tirelessly pursues his kidnapped princess and her captors into the frozen Northern lands of the yellow men of Mars.<br/><br/>This is a disappointing finale to the trilogy that begins Edgar Rice Burroughs’s Barsoom series. Impossible coincidences and plot developments that can only happen because a main character is stupid or careless have always been unfortunate tropes of the Burroughs oeuvre, but sheer breathless storytelling and classic pulp fun are usually sufficient to overcome these short</span>
  <span id="freeText2306483614444198526" style="display:none">John Carter tirelessly pursues his kidnapped princess and her captors into the frozen Northern lands of the yellow men of Mars.<br /><br />This is a disappointing finale to the trilogy that begins Edgar Rice Burroughs’s Barsoom series. Impossible coincidences and plot developments that can only happen because a main character is stupid or careless have always been unfortunate tropes of the Burroughs oeuvre, but sheer breathless storytelling and classic pulp fun are usually sufficient to overcome these shortcomings. This time, however, the plotting seems particularly sloppy. Coincidence is required to propel the story forward at virtually every point. A few stunning lapses in judgement and logic make Carter appear to be not only the greatest fighting man of two worlds but also the dimmest bulb. Burroughs really hit on an interesting device when Carter is given a crystal that resonates in proximity to similar crystals held by secret agents who can assist him, but he doesn’t work hard enough to exploit it to its fullest potential. Still, even subpar ERB has its pleasures.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="2306483614444198526" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


