    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2841372285" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2841372285" />
    <a title="Joseph Carrabis" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/47112679-joseph-carrabis"><img alt="Joseph Carrabis" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1443638212p2/47112679.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2841372285?book_show_action=true">May 31, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Joseph Carrabis" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Joseph Carrabis" href="/user/show/47112679-joseph-carrabis">Joseph Carrabis</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2841372285" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12936883211509598771">I continued down the glass spiraled staircase realizing the yellow-skinned Okarians could do not but jeer at me, as I mentioned in <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2841369032' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Gods of Mars</a>.<br/>Okay, seriously, once I started Burroughs’s Barsoom series I found it difficult to stop. Everything I wrote in <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2841364675' rel='nofollow noopener'>A Princess of Mars</a> and The Gods of Mars holds here. Excellent read for both reader and writer developing their craft.<br/>What’s most amazing to me is the rich world-building Burroughs does and in so few words. Each novel (thus far) puts Carter i</span>
  <span id="freeText12936883211509598771" style="display:none">I continued down the glass spiraled staircase realizing the yellow-skinned Okarians could do not but jeer at me, as I mentioned in <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2841369032" rel="nofollow noopener">The Gods of Mars</a>.<br />Okay, seriously, once I started Burroughs’s Barsoom series I found it difficult to stop. Everything I wrote in <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2841364675" rel="nofollow noopener">A Princess of Mars</a> and The Gods of Mars holds here. Excellent read for both reader and writer developing their craft.<br />What’s most amazing to me is the rich world-building Burroughs does and in so few words. Each novel (thus far) puts Carter in a new part of Mars. Much of the previous novel’s world-building doesn’t appear until near the end, when Carter gets out of “this” book’s scrap, wins the prize, makes it home (to Helium, not Earth), et cetera. As such, he builds a new world with each novel. Impressive. Also worth noting is that each novel is pretty much the same story (as noted in A Princess of Mars): boy-meets-girl, boy-loses-girl, boy-beats-up-everything-in-sight, boy-gets-girl story. <br />Not that it matters recognizing that. Still ripping good yarns.<br />One final note: That “Warlord of Mars” thing. It almost seems tacked on, as if Burroughs said, “Oh, darn! I forgot about that. Better add it now.” It’s also amusing that, at the end of this novel, Carter has pretty much united all the different peoples of Mars hence warlords are no longer necessary. Kind of like giving someone a meaningless title to make them feel important.<br />And reading that last section, realizing the title was irrelevant in the current political climate at the close of the novel, is when I also realized the importance of “Just tell a good story.” Don’t worry about everything else, it’ll come. First, just tell a good story.<br />Thanks, Ed.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="12936883211509598771" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


